/*! Wabi-Sabi: A Japanese Aesthetic of Imperfection and Transience

Wabi-sabi (侘寂) is a fundamental concept in Japanese aesthetics that emphasizes the beauty of imperfection, impermanence, and the simplicity of natural things. It's often associated with the idea of finding beauty in the transient and imperfect aspects of life. This concept is deeply rooted in Zen Buddhism and has been a significant influence on various art forms in Japan, such as tea ceremony, pottery, and garden design.

